			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				X~ just to redirect the topic a bit and hijack.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Fitness is a measure of reproductive success </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />

<br />
From Xianin's link. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> If you are faster and stronger than I am, it does you no good if you can not breed. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Keep in mind, fitness is a combination of several factors. 
<br />

<br />
You have Direct Fitness, which how many viable offspring you have compared to the rest of your species. Keep in mind, direct fitness doesn't look at your offspring, but your offspring's offspring. The quality of life of your offspring greatly affects how many descendants it will have (so having less is sometimes greater than having many).
<br />

<br />
Then you have indirect fitness, where by improving the quality of life for your brother/sister/niece/nephew increases your fitness as a whole. Your genetic material is what is important~ your sister is 50% related to you. Your offspring is 50% related to you. Your sister's offspring is 25% related to you. If you increase your sister's offspring's quantity of offspring by 100% by offering support, and increasing the quality of life, then you essentially had one kid's worth of offspring yourself. Perfect example.. Ants, bees, and wasps. The vast majority of these insects are sterile, yet they increase the quality of life by doing most of the labor in the hive. (most of these insects are 80% related to each other, through haplodiploidy)
<br />

<br />
So you do not necessarily need to breed yourself to be biologically fit.
<br />

<br />
(granted, i do agree with xianin in his post asside from the "we are no longer evolving" point, just thought i'd throw this idea into the mix).<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
