		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=71941&amp;sid=82260115d6e1a7fd6d33fd52a8a3fef5#71941"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Wed Jun 23, 2004 2:35 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Excerpt from &quot;The Isaiah Effect&quot;</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=71941&amp;sid=82260115d6e1a7fd6d33fd52a8a3fef5"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Raviel, as to your remarks about stuff like cracking the human genome, they have been working on that for well over ten years Heck, I bet one of the first things that Watson and Crick (the 'discoverers' of DNA) was that it needs to be decoded and that was a bit over 50 years ago. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You completely missed my point. Ten years ago, they said they would never be able to finish it because mankind would never have the computing power necessary to completely decode it. That has nothing to do with when they started it. Is it not bloody obvious that in the last year of decoding the genome they accomplished more than in all of the fifty some-odd years previous? How can you see technological growth like that and willfully ignore it?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Raviel to touch on what you mentioned, a perfect example in the modern world are these undeveloped countries that we have. We are going to evolve as a species, but eventually everybody in the world will be held back due to the less developed parts of the world; growth will stagnate. When those countries/civilizations get 'caught up' then we again will evolve. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Eventually these lesser-developed parts of the world will develop. They will either do it on their own, or the more developed parts of the world will do it for them. Their development is essential for the continuance of the development of all areas of the world, and so it will happen sooner or later. I do agree however that these underdeveloped areas will hold back the more developed ones... that's the main reason I think Kurzweil's timeline is off. It's a drag on his exponential curve that isn't taken into account.
<br />

<br />
You can see this development starting already... the EU, India, China, even Iraq, are all more developed now than they were last year. Their development remains slow because they are at the bottom of the curve, but as they continue to develop, the pace of development they experience will continue to increase just as it has for the more developed regions of the world. History proves this... at the very least they will follow in the footsteps of western civilization, and at the best they may exceed it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Also I feel that you do not give the everday Joe Blow enough credit. Like it or not, the fact is that masses rule the world: masses = joe blow. There are, obviously, the thinkers and leaders but they are only as good as the Joe Blows. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
What a load of crap. Joe Blow can barely balance his checkbook and stay out of debt. Joe Blow is earning minimum wage, or on welfare with 5 kids. Joe blow is content to ignore everything about the world that doesn't intrude into his own little shell, and he views anything that requires him to step out of it as a personal attack. All men may be created equal, but they sure as hell don't stay that way. All one has to do is look at the structure of human society to see this. Joe blow tills the fields, pumps the gas, waits tables, and basically does all the work that isn't fit for the more advanced people to do. The people who rule this world are the same people that always rule this world... the ones with the money. The only time Joe blow has any power is when he picks up a pitchfork and kills all of his rulers (and in that respect, he is the most powerful force)... but then he goes right back to indifference afterwards, so that brief moment of lucidity counts for very little in the long run. I'd love for this to change, but I think we're a hell of a long way out from that. 
<br />

<br />
Despite Joe blow's indifference or inability (whichever it is) to better himself, he's come a long way from being a serf working for a knight out of fear of being killed or thrown off the knight's lands to starve. These days, he's a drone working for a corporation because if he doesn't, he'll have no money to live on and he'll starve. He has more freedom now, and a FAR better standard of living than he ever has before, and in exchange for this he simply puts in his time fueling the economy that provides the foundation for everything. There is a sharp increase in the degree of efficiency here... Joe blow's efforts are more productive now than when he was a serf.
<br />

<br />
Yes, there are still serfs out there in the world. Most of them now have the option of programming in India or working in a sneaker factory in Bangladesh if they want. Everybody's situation has not improved, but for many it has. As I said, this sort of limiting factor is the only thing I see wrong with Kurzweil's thesis... his timeline is off because of the drag caused by underdeveloped areas. This drag will not stop the growth, it will only slow it down some.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I fall into a crowd of people who believe that human technology has essentially nullified any sort of biological evolution that has taken place. Biological evolution is going to, essentialy, cease to be as there is an increase in technology. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
You're almost there. Technology has indeed killed evolution dead for humanity, but did you ever stop to think about why this happened? It's because we were able to use it to <span style="font-style: italic">nullify</span> the effects of evolution. If it can nullify evolution, why do you insist that it can't enhance it as well? Nanotechnology alone can stop every ailment of the human body... there is litreally no form of disease or disorder that cannot be cured by nanotech and gene therapy. Both of those technologies are here now, they are not some far fetched scifi theory... they are tested, and they are proven to do exactly what they claim to do... make death the kind of thing that happens only by accident or suicide. It is within the realm of science fact that in 50 years time, you pop a pill and after that, you can kiss bad health goodbye permanently.
<br />

<br />
That's pretty far outside evolution, but it is evolution. Through technology and engineering, we will have built DNA sequencing and an immune system that nature couldn't provide us with over billions of years. Now you tell me what's more powerful in that scenario, technology or evolution?
<br />

<br />
Kurzweil can ignore biological evolution because it is <span style="font-style: italic">irrelevant</span>. It no longer effects us, and in the near future technological evolution, controlled by our brightest minds, will replace it, and technological evolution does not follow Darwin's laws. Errors in technological evolution can be fixed as fast as they arise, unlike in nature where death and reproduction and a lot of time is required to get anything done.
<br />

<br />
If you eliminate death, do you any longer need to reproduce? You do see how the very idea of reproduction becomes obsolete, right? Especially if you can liberate the consciousness to a point where it is not dependent on a body. Any time you are faced with death, you transmit elsewhere into another medium. It's a logical extension of what humans will do with technology. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> We as a species have no major need or reason to develop some leap in evolution. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Need? Surely not, you're right about that. However, it's very clear we WANT to do it. There are many reasons... how much will you pay to add 50 years to your life? Double your cognitive capability by clearing out and improving neural pathways? We can say we want to do these things because they provide us a better quality of life (that's the good-guy viewpoint anyway.) In truth, greed, as always, will motivate it all. Someone will pay for life extension, and so life extension will be created, refined, cheapened, perfected, adaptec to fit society's needs, and used.
<br />

<br />
I think you're quite right in that we're reaching the <span style="font-style: italic">natural</span> limit of what our technology and medicine can do for us by chemically enhancing our bodies, but you're not thinking far enough ahead and seeing what we can do by redesigning the body completely, and replacing some of its systems with our own. We have artificial hearts, artificial immune systems are on the way real soon now, and shortly after that will be artificial life as they slow aging down by providing you with all the telomere strings you can use.
<br />

<br />
The brain is the toughest nut to crack, by far, and it will surely be the final frontier in understanding the human body, but it will fall, just as everything else does, to the relentless advance of technology as man tries to find a purpose and answer that damnable question: "Why?"
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I would like to see some more studies about reverse engineering the brain, as Kurzweil mentions. However, I think in a typicial computer-type person way, he fails to tkae notice that the brain is not some stand alone organ. In the technology world you can increase HDD space, RAM, video and whatever else all as stand alone advnaces. Sure everything eventually needs to take a leap forward, but I can buy a bigger HDD right now without upgrading my entire computer. You can not, though, rebuild the brain via reverse engineering in the same fashion. Simple and easy explanation is the hormone regulation that happens in the body. Stuff enters and leaves the brain (so to speak) so the brain is not neccesarily isolated. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Irrelevant. If the entire body has to be fruned and understood, then it will be. The complexity of the system will pose no barrier because there will be no barrier sufficient to overcome advances in technology. 
<br />

<br />
Essentially, any argument that is based on the premise of "we will never understand _____ " is built on nothing. There is nothing in this universe that we cannot learn, nothing we cannot do, nothing we cannot change, nothing we cannot understand, nothing we cannot duplicate. It's merely a question of the time and resources involved in pulling the mystery apart and solving it. What's more, we alone have the capability to bring things into existence that are not in the universe right now. If quantum and classical computers prove unequal to the task, mankind will invent something else that isn't.
<br />

<br />
The only argument that works is the argument that our technology will hit a ceiling and stop. So far, if you argue that point, you're arguing against the example set by the entirety of human history, and that makes you the crackpot. As I pointed out earlier, computers are just getting started, and they'll blow by Moore's law like a F22 blowing by a seagull. Quantum computers defy Moore's law, because Moore's law comes from the classical computing era. It has as much relevance on quantum computers as laws about the abacus have on classicl computers. Computing power (or, cognitive power if you want to seperate it from machines) is the number one requisite quantity for Kurzweil's predictions, and it is not going to slow down in our lifetimes, if ever.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
