				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Errors in technological evolution can be fixed as fast as they arise,</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> Bzzzt. Wrong. Until 1970 virtually all of the US corn crop used something called "texas male sterile cytoplasm" (TMSC). Fancy word for a strain of corn that had sterile male flowers. It was used in all the hybrid breeding lines. A particular strain of rust (fancy farmer word for <span style="font-style: italic">mold</span>) was highly damaging to corn with TMSC. As early as 1966, reports indicated that TMSC corn could be wiped out by rusts, but the seed industry didn't give a damn. If the weather conditions didn't break in the summer of 1970, all of the commercial corn crop would have been wiped out instead of only 30%. They only did something when they were pissing in their pants from panic. That was 5 years after the first symptoms, and just a couple weeks from total crop failure.
<br />

<br />
Sit down with a copy of Altered Harvests. You will change your tune pretty fast.
<br />

<br />
People can't even agree on global warming or the war on iraq. What makes you think they are all suddenly going to get religion and notice when something unpalatable to some political group in <span style="font-style: italic">technological evolution</span> occurs? It won't happen. Hell, it took almost 60 years for folks to agree that cigarettes are bad for you, and the tobacco companies are still fighting it. It took the AMA 120 years to agree that your diet has an effect on your health. It took almost 10 years for the governments in europe to agree that mad cow disease could spread to humans by eating beef. Genetically modified foods safe or not? Genetically modified people safe or not? Nah, folks will argue about whether gene GH5235 is good or bad until the sun goes dark. People currently won't agree on simple stuff let alone stuff that takes a phd to figure out. Plus trying to figure out if the people that lied in the past are telling the truth now is not going to make it easier. And the organizations we have to help us figure out whether they are safe or not have been corrupted by politics. Safe or not? The safe answer is to say: no.
<br />

<br />
By the way. Moore's law is an observation. Marketing departments have been trying to make engineering match the "prophesy" but they are coming to the hard core limits pretty soon. Transistors won't work if you use less than one electron to make them switch. If you treat moores law as a marketing gimmick, you won't be disappointed. If you act as if it is some sort of meaningful thing, you will get your rear burned off when the bubble bursts. Computers may get orders of magnitude faster, but we still use 1960s technology for writing the software for them. Even though we have had 40 years of programming fads pretending to be the latest silver bullet. You won't see useful quantum computers before you retire.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
