			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Rav, I don't even know where to start replying to your fanciful representation of the human condition and the future of human evolution. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />
Start by discussing the only point in the entire mess that matters: technology is growing, the rate it grows by is growing, the number of people affected by it is growing, and the number of things we can do with it is growing. Everything else is natural progression from that one simple fact. We can throw stardust around all day about what the technology may or may not bring about, debate who's got a more realistic viewpoint of Earth's huddled masses, or argue about the steepness of the advancement curve, but the conclusion remains the same. If you're going to tell me we can't ever decode the mind from the body you'd better use arguments better than the ones people used claiming television would never work or that we couldn't put a man on the moon. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Bzzzt. Wrong. Until 1970 virtually all of the US corn crop used something called "texas male sterile cytoplasm" (TMSC). </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Yes. I never said people wouldn't make mistakes... heck mistakes with this kind of technology are by far the greatest danger we face. If you check, however, I'll wager that particular oversight has been caught and corrected in current genetically modified crops. Do they not do checks regularly to make sure they aren't engineering something that doesn't stand a chance in the wild? My point still stands... there's no reason they can't fix that problem in a short time frame and switch to a crop that hasn't got that problem. It doesn't take millions of years of evolution... it takes a few rocket scientists, some very big computers, a little tenacity, and a little time.
<br />

<br />
As far as people not agreeing on everything, that's nothing new. I think you'll find that when you dangle immortality in front of them, however, they'll happily agree to take it and then argue about if it was the right decision until the stars burn out. The ones who don't will be in the (dying) minority. The population with the largest lifespan will always be the winner because they never lose their talented people or their accumulated skill sets (which continue to grow forever). The rest can join or perish, the outcome is the same either way. IIt'll be far easier to place restrictions on new life being created (heck China already does it) than it will be to convince people not to take a magic pill that's going to cause some overpopulation problems.
<br />

<br />
My whole point about Moore's law was that it isn't meaningful. It's far too conservative. There won't be any bursting of a computer bubble, because hardware development is not going to slow down. Everyone is always moaning about the molecular limits of computing technology when they do not matter in the slightest... if we hit a physical limit, we just make the damn chip bigger and add more transistors, more layers, and more intelligent design to keep on doubling the potential for as long as we keep needing them. There's no reason a computer can't be as big as a warehouse, especially with optical circuitry coming along nicely. There is no law that says a CPU has to be smaller than your thumbnail, you know. That's just a matter of convenience and bad power design, not necessity.
<br />

<br />
As for quantum computers, the first prototype quantum processor was built in 2001. Plenty of high-IQs have been theorizing the software and computing algorithms for decades, so we're already ahead in that department. They are on target to get the workings of a funtional quantum system down within 20 years, and you can't imagine the amount of money being poured into quantum research. I expect to see the first generation of quantum in supercomputing centers by 2020. That's long before classical computers will have run out of steam. Even if the most dire predictions about classical computing bottlenecks pan out, quantum will be right there to take over when classical hits this mythical performance barrier.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
