			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I'll wager that particular oversight has been caught and corrected in current genetically modified crops. Do they not do checks regularly to make sure they aren't engineering something that doesn't stand a chance in the wild?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> No. They don't. Don't bet more than 1 beer. They spend more time figuring out how to sue folks. Whether its SLAPP lawsuits against the folks afraid of gmo, or sueing folks like <a href="http://slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=04/05/21/1653238&mode=thread&tid=123&tid=134&tid=155&tid=191&tid=99" target="_blank" class="postlink">Schmeiser</a> when their crops get out of control.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">There's no reason a computer can't be as big as a warehouse</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">Yes, there are. Two of them are called power dissipation and clock skew. Making the trannies smaller cuts down on both. Early alpha cpus got so hot that if the fan fell off, the chip would desolder itself. Making it bigger makes it unpredictable enough that you don't know if the one you made even works. Make the trannies too small and the alpha particles given off by the black epoxy will rip through the circuits causing upsets. That started to become a problem in the mid 1980s. When you start talking about clock times of 1Ghz, you are talking about free space wavelengths of 10 inches (more like 3 inches in silicon). When the distances signals travel start to approach 20% of the wavelength, you get into major trouble with phase problems. In a modern cpu, between 5 and 10% of the chip area is devoted to making that stupid clock work and get distributed cleanly around the chip. And you have to treat everything as a transmission line.
<br />

<br />
Can you throw more computers at the task? Sure, they have been doing that sort of thing since the 1960s. MIMD and SIMD machines have been around since then, most were invented for weather forecasting. There still are no good parallel programming languages.
<br />

<br />
You aren't an engineer. You aren't a scientist. If you were, you would realize your ideas are so far outside current material science that major breakthroughs would be needed. The kind that overthrows everything we have and makes current technology look positively 1700s. Those might come along. But I won't hold my breath. Go ahead and dream, but call it what it is: fantasy.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
