<br />
There are no good commercial parallel programming languages.  There are excellent parallel programming libraries that are held by private houses for older processors and patents on algos.  There is no viable market for parallel processing yet except for specialty applications.
<br />

<br />
Demand will change this and I think that is EvilKnights point.
<br />

<br />
I notice that you do not argue that parallel programming is unheard of nor that it is impossible with todays tech.  EKs argument is based wholely on what is not only possible now but what is possible tomarrow and what will be possible one day.
<br />

<br />
Leaps in technology, like evolution, are not unheard of.  Matter of fact it tends to be the rule.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">You aren't an engineer. You aren't a scientist. If you were, you would realize your ideas are so far outside current material science that major breakthroughs would be needed.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The problem with scientists are that they are generally a narrowminded lot.  Narrowminded in that they specialize and rarely think outside of the box except where they actively research.  Engineers on the other hand are a different breed.
<br />

<br />
Tang I would hazard to guess that you are not an engineer but that EK is.  Engineers deal on  plane of "how to" and "can do".  Scientists dwell so much on "does it or does it not".  The application of scientific discoveries belongs in the hands of people who make things not the ones that get paid to argue about them.
<br />

<br />
Most of EKs arguments do not require leaps in science.  They require leaps in technology.  Science has already demonstrated the effect.  working around physical limitations in chip size, density, and getting away from planar form, is also a matter of technological achievement not scientific revolution.
<br />

<br />
The industry is gear for and tooled for decreasing transistor size.  Other methods of increasing computing power have not been explored because it is not economicly feasible when current trends are still viable.  Getting away from panar arrangements for CPUs is a matter of jumping some expensive hurdles in manufacturing not in science.
<br />

<br />
Another of EKs points seems to be that the building blocks of quantum computing have been discovered.  "How to" make it stable and usable is not the realm of science it is the realm of technology.  It is not a matter of "if" anymore it is a matter of when.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The kind that overthrows everything we have and makes current technology look positively 1700s.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
What we have now makes the 1940s look positively 1700s.  Not a good argument.
<br />

<br />
Leaps in discovery are a rule not an exception they happen with a regularity that is directly connected to market demand.  If you were an engineer or a scientist you would realize that yourself.  A real scientist would never say "impossible" they would say "improbable and not clearly demonstrated". A real engineer never says "impossible" they say "curiously improbable got any research funds?"
<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
With the leaps made in entanglement just recently announced as demonstrated and reprocucable, EKs Quantum computer is a closer reality and no longer a thing of fantasy.  Tang, I'm certain you are out of your field and may not realize the impact this technological breakthrough WILL have. 
<br />

<br />
if YOU are a scientist you probably have a subscription to nature:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.nature.com/cgi-taf/DynaPage.taf?file=/nature/journal/v429/n6993/full/nature02608_fs.html" target="_blank">http://www.nature.com/cgi-taf/DynaPage.taf?file=/nature/journal/v429/n6993/full/nature02608_fs.html</a>
<br />

<br />
If not a breif explanation is in this NIST press release
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The ions were teleported inside a NIST-developed multi-zone trap, first described in 2002. Lasers are used to manipulate the ion?s spin and motion, and to entangle the ions by linking their internal spin states to their external motion. A key technical advance reported in the current paper is the capability to entangle ions and then separate them in the trap (maintaining entanglement) without generating much heat. This previously led to uncontrolled motions that interfered with operations and required additional cooling operations. The advance was enabled in part by the use of smaller electrodes to generate electric fields that move the ions between trap zones.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
