				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Leaps in technology, like evolution, are not unheard of. Matter of fact it tends to be the rule. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Nope. That is not a fully supported argument at this point in time. Currently there is a debate going on between Punctuated Evolution and Gradual Evolution. Granted, I believe the truth is a combination of both theorems, to date the vast majority of the scientific community follow the Gradual Evolution theory.
<br />

<br />
Technology is a different breed. Technology does not evolve as you might suggest. For instance, Biological evolution relies on last year's model to produce todays design. 
<br />

<br />
i.e. your spine is not designed for bipedal movement, yet you use it for bipedal movement anyway. There are a lot better designs that are a) cost effective, b) more structurally sound. However, we did not have the building blocks to move to a better designed spine. SO we're stuck with a quadruped spine rigged to operate as a poor bipedal spine. (Thus so many people have back problems).
<br />

<br />

<br />
If you're trying to design an engine for a plane, you don't take a car engine and rig it to work in a plane. Instead you start your designs from scratch. &lt;--- This stops Technology from resembling evolution. Technology may advance, but it does not do it in a Darwinian sense.
<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> The problem with scientists are that they are generally a narrowminded lot. Narrowminded in that they specialize and rarely think outside of the box except where they actively research. Engineers on the other hand are a different breed.
<br />

<br />
Engineers deal on plane of "how to" and "can do". Scientists dwell so much on "does it or does it not".
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I am both a scientist and an engineer.
<br />
Id hazard to guess that you have very little clue what youre talking about and that Rav is daydreaming about Tomorrow Land at Disney. The types of leaps in technology will require major breakthroughs the magnitude of the discovery of capacitors, natural selection, calculus, and ect.
<br />

<br />
A scientist will look at this situation and say Is it possible? Not today, or anytime soon, but sure An engineer would look at this situation and say Possible? Sure. Probable? Probably not with the cost of todays resources, the current economy, few companies to fund the project for the next hundred years with few products, and  (never ending statement of a list of requirements youd need for this daydream fantasy to occur)
<br />

<br />
P.S. Poppa, not every scientist has a subscription to Nature. Instead, you can usually go down to your local university and browse most Journals if you're so inclined. Plus, the items discussed in Nature might not interest most Scientists. Only a few branches of Biologists could I envision subscribing to nature, and of those mostly professors and researchers. There are other, more specialized, less prestigious journals to be found to spend your money on.<br />
