				<div class="postbody">
				My first degree was in electrical engineering. I went to design integrated circuits.
<br />

<br />
Engineering is about how to solve problems. It is not about how to make wild stuff up: that is the job of marketing. And that is why marketing is the natural enemy of engineering.
<br />

<br />
It is a huge step from making a few gates out of quantum doohickeys to making a computer: most of which have thousands to millions of gates.
<br />

<br />
All of the companies making parallel processors have gone out of business or been purchased at chapter 11/13 fire sales. Maybe you can buy some transputers around on ebay. More economical methods of processing things in parallel are to use distributed processing. Like that warehouse of undepreciated pentium 75s that were at a past company. Instead of being allowed to purchase some 4-processor xeon box, I ended up converting the code to dcom, using one box as a scheduler and getting the tasks done for the company with the resources available.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
