<br />
That's really unfortunate, but sadly typical of humanity. I wonder if they'll add in checks like that once they become trivially easy to do. Shouldn't take too much longer with the progression in genetics and computation these days. Is there no regluatory/advisory board overseeing this sort of thing? It seems rather daft to be risking food crops on a game of genetic russian roulette.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Yes, there are. Two of them are called power dissipation and clock skew. Making the trannies smaller cuts down on both. Early alpha cpus got so hot that if the fan fell off, the chip would desolder itself. Making it bigger makes it unpredictable enough that you don't know if the one you made even works. Make the trannies too small and the alpha particles given off by the black epoxy will rip through the circuits causing upsets. That started to become a problem in the mid 1980s. When you start talking about clock times of 1Ghz, you are talking about free space wavelengths of 10 inches (more like 3 inches in silicon). When the distances signals travel start to approach 20% of the wavelength, you get into major trouble with phase problems. In a modern cpu, between 5 and 10% of the chip area is devoted to making that stupid clock work and get distributed cleanly around the chip. And you have to treat everything as a transmission line. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
<a href="http://science.nasa.gov/newhome/headlines/msad18may99_1.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink"> Sorry, you lose. </a> <a href="http://www.eetimes.com/at/news/OEG20040216S0019" target="_blank" class="postlink">You really should keep abreast of the cutting edge developments in computer technology,</a> and stop basing all of your arguments and assumptions on engineering that is becoming outdated. All you do is change from electronic to photonic circuitry (we've had it since the late 1990s) and your distance and heat problems vanish. I mentioned that earlier, you must have missed it, or dismissed it as so much fantasy.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">"The thin-films allow us to transmit information using light. And because we're working with light, we're working with the speed of light without generating as much heat as electrons," says Frazier. "We can move information faster than electronic circuits, and without the need to remove damaging heat."</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Move classical computers from electronic to photonic and you'll get an order-of-magnitude improvement in their efficiency and power. Toss in a quantum computing unit and you'll find that Moore's law is the fantasy. People will be looking back on it and laughing about it just as hard as they laugh about the guys that claimed you'd never need more than 640K of memory.
<br />

<br />
Here's a thought for you. They have been experimenting with sending lasers through fiber optic cables for some time now, and <a href="http://www.linktionary.com/w/wdm.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">have found they can parallelize the communications by sending multiple beams of differently colored light over the same cable,</a> with the only limitation being the complexity of the receiver required at both ends. Care to extend that parallel data path concept to optical processors and expound a bit on what it could do for them?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Nope. That is not a fully supported argument at this point in time. Currently there is a debate going on between Punctuated Evolution and Gradual Evolution. Granted, I believe the truth is a combination of both theorems, to date the vast majority of the scientific community follow the Gradual Evolution theory. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This is true. The popularly held belief is that evolution is generally very gradual, however every so often there is a brief period of time where it speeds up wildly before slowing back down again, usually in response to something happening in the environment. You'll find most scientists hold the opinion that we are in one of those fast phases right now. Human meddling with everything under the sun is causing many changes to the earth, and change means evolution.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Technology is a different breed. Technology does not evolve as you might suggest. For instance, Biological evolution relies on last year's model to produce todays design. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
So does technology. One example I just read was a method for switching beams in optical routers using heat bubbles. This was first used in ink-jet printers years ago. There are a billion examples of this kind of technological cross-pollination. Engineers and scientists always look at how things were done yesterday to better derive how best to do them tomorrow. Most of your computer pgorams use standard libraries that were written years ago to do all sorts of new things. Technology is actually very good at avoiding re-inventing the wheel, at least when politics and patents don't get in the way.
<br />

<br />
You'd be far better off thinking of technology as <span style="font-style: italic">self-directed evolution.</span>
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Id hazard to guess that you have very little clue what youre talking about and that Rav is daydreaming about Tomorrow Land at Disney. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
It's bloody obvious that you've got your nose so close to the ground that you can't see what's on either side of you or on the horizon. Or maybe you're unwilling to accept it. These leaps of technology you speak of have already <span style="font-style: italic">been made</span> and are on their way through the development process, getting closer every day.
<br />

<br />
I won't deny the cost. The cost is tremendous. It's also irrelevant, because the cost will be paid; it's inevitable. All cost can do is delay it for a little while. What do you think it would have cost in 1940 to put a computer more powerful than the <a href="http://ftp.arl.mil/~mike/comphist/eniac-story.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">ENIAC</a> into a <a href="http://www.freeos.com/articles/3800" target="_blank" class="postlink">wristwatch?</a> Yet we did it. If you'd asked any engineer and most scientists back then if such a thing were possible, they'd have laughed you out of the room. They were wrong, just as you are. They however had the benefit of being in a time when technology was just emerging... you live in a time when technology dominates every aspect of life. You should know better, give the ability to observe technology's history and current research.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> <a href="http://www.freeos.com/articles/3800" target="_blank" class="postlink"> a "Watch PC" imagine your watch having the computing power of "latter" (few years old) day laptop.</a> </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
That linux watch has more power than the first laptop computers, by a long shot. It's far ahead of the 286/386 Compaq Models (lite-20) or the Epson NB3. Not much of a stretch of the imagination, though you can't buy them yet. Won't be long, though.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> With all the functions and interfaces. Your watch can hold the processor, ram, etc and run on kinetic energy stored by your movements daily, and with a small camera that points up. You put on a pair of glasses, or a monocle that gives an image of a keyboard, when you type your fingers go to the 'place' where the key would be, and the camera senses that, inputting it into the watch. with a small extendable usb cord, or when wireless technology becomes more seamless, everyone would have their own PDA/Personal Computer - and I'm sure with advents in cell technology/nano technology, we could eventually implant this into a persons arm/skin - eliminating the need for the watch altogether, and powering the computer with bio-energy that we generate of our own accord. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Well, we have a <a href="http://www.technologyreview.com/articles/rnb_101703.asp" target="_blank" class="postlink">10-megabit body bus design</a> using your body's skin as the transport layer. Brings new meaning to the term "personal area network." That takes care of cords, we don't need them. Consider that it's only a matter of time before citywide wireless networks emerge (and form countrywide wireless ones shortly thereafter) and cell phone links for those in rural areas (or planetwide if <a href="http://www.teledesic.com/d%efault.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">Teledesic</a> ever gets off the ground) and you've got wireless internet everywhere all the time. <a href="http://www.media.mit.edu/wearables/" target="_blank" class="postlink">There are plenty of existing prototypes for wearable interfaces</a> right now. As for energy, <a href="http://www.space.com/businesstechnology/technology/body_power_011128-1.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">they have ideas for human-powered devices,</a> but that's a bit of a stretch right now I think... we'll more likely be using fuel cells for some time to come.
<br />

<br />
I'd say 10-15 years is a reasonable estimate for powerful, well designed wearble computers. The hardest part of building them will be the interface design, however, not the technology. Intelligent interface design is damn hard.
<br />

