			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Rav, Im not saying that your fanciful idea of our future reality is impossible, and I do not believe Xianin or Tangurena would say it is impossible either. What we are saying, that the ideas you proposed to be absolute truth in Kurzweils article are highly improbable in the timeframe that was proposed. 
<br />

<br />
No engineer or scientist would ever say a given possibility is 100% impossible. Who knows what tomorrow will bring. 
<br />

<br />
However, due to your, poppas and Kurzweils poor conception of what evolution is about and how the inner workings in the thoughts of the Evolution Theory fit together, and our current understanding of the human mind (note I said mind, not brain as youre all saying brains will no longer be needed in a few years!), your ideas are pure fantasy for today, tomorrow, and anytime in the near future.
<br />

<br />
I honestly suggest you should read Pinkers How the Mind works. It is a great book, and might give you a bit of insight to what we currently think of the Mind. (Note this book is not definitive! To date, there exists no definitive work on how the mind really works. This is one version/idea of the reality, as we understand it).
<br />

<br />
As for you seeing a high rate of evolution in todays ever-changing world due to human interaction? Id like to see some primary research that might suggest this is the case. Everything is always facing selective pressures (yes, humans included; Although our pressures are mainly sexual selective in nature, as we are our own environment of evolutionary adaptiveness). Due to the radical changes we bring to todays environment, and due to the specie pollution we have introduced for the past four hundred years, Id say more species are going extinct than are radically changing. 
<br />

<br />
Looking at a holistic view of the world and time, you would probably see a flurry of gradual changes in this period. One might argue Punctuated Evolution from that case, but as I said, the more likely case is a hybrid of both the Punctuated Evolution and Gradual Evolution ideas to be a more realistic model (Something many biologists consider to be the case).
<br />

<br />
Remember also, that the key problem with suggesting that technology follows an evolutionary path itself is that you can always design an optimal tool/device. You cannot however design an optimal biological organism to ANY environment using evolution. Technology improves as time goes on, however it does not follow evolutionary trends. Improvement over time!= evolution in a biological sense, and relating technology and biology improvements in such a fashion ends there. 
<br />

<br />
Furthermore, any argument Kurzweil has in his article about evolution is false. He argues that evolution is on an exponential increase in changes. It does not however follow such a trend. It may have become more rapid compared to the early period of single celled organisms, especially when sexual replication came about, however that increase in the rate of evolution does not suggest that all species follow a similar trend. Species themselves do not evolve faster today than they did yesterday. Even looking at all species holistically and monitoring change, youll probably note that the rate of evolution is both indirectly dependant upon the average generation time of a population and directly dependant upon the rate of change an environment has.
<br />

<br />
Technology however, improves by a rate that is dependant upon cost, business possibility, application, the amount of engineers put to the task, recent breakthroughs in science, interest in the project, marketability, and ect.
<br />

<br />
You have seen a recent increase in the rate of which new technologies come about, however that is due to the amount of money that is gained by providing new technologies, combined with the amount of new engineers that are entering the new technologies field. 
<br />

<br />
keep in mind, your personal computer may be powerful and smart, however take a look at the PCM in your car, or the Power distribution box or junction box in your car and realize that those technologies are, in some cases, decades old. Why? Because it is not cost effective to improve them beyond their current states.
<br />

<br />
MAIN POINT: Techonolgy only improves in todays world if there is money to be made. It is not an evolutionary process just because it improves.  This is world is not a member of the Federation in Star Trek.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
