				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Is there no regulatory/advisory board overseeing this sort of thing? It seems rather daft to be risking food crops on a game of genetic russian roulette</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> No. There isn't. That was the point of Altered Harvests. The vast majority (based on calories consumed) of the food crops are grains. Only 1 in the top 20 food crops is a "tree" (although I don't consider palm trees to be real trees, they lack lignin).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">That's really unfortunate, but sadly typical of humanity. I wonder if they'll add in checks like that once they become trivially easy to do. Shouldn't take too much longer with the progression in genetics and computation these days.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> If genetic engineering becomes trivial, you should become very scared. I can consider several thingies that will result in a lot of grief:
<br />
1 - one cure to end racism: a retrovirus to turn everyone the same color black.
<br />
2 - some racist's cure to end racism: a retrovirus that kills anyone who is black.
<br />
3 - a cure to islamic terrorism: a retrovirus that kills everyone who lets carpet touch their forehead.
<br />
4 - the jihadi counterversion: a retrovirus that kills everyone who does not.
<br />
5 - an assasination virus designed to kill one person and any twins or clones they have.
<br />
6 - an ecoterrorist virus: designed to kill off plants or animals important to some economy, like cattle, or camels or corn.
<br />
7 - an anti terrorist/landmine bacteria: designed to eat nitrated compounds used in explosives. yummy, semtex, burp.
<br />
8 - Mutant 59 - the Plastic Eaters. A classic 1974 sci-fi thriller.
<br />

<br />
The stuff needed to sequence and make your own "germs" is pretty easy to get. No controls, just send money. An early novel describing it would be Frank Herbert's <span style="font-style: italic">White Plague</span>. 
<br />

<br />
Human factors are very important. The reason many technologies die miserable deaths has a lot to do with HF. Marketing and social issues also tend to affect market adoption or failure.
<br />

<br />
Optronics (or photonics) has been lab stuff for 20+ years. We've had it since the late 70s. I will believe when I see chips come out. Don't forget using holograms to connect different parts of a die with each other. That's 20 years old too. You can easily drag up 20 year old references to SPIE articles on optical computing (in case you don't know, that's the technical society that concerns itself with optical engineering). That doesn't make it the amazing new stuff like you think it is. Moving classical computers to optronics would be more like 6-10 orders of magnitude reduction in heat and energy consumption. If it were commercially viable, you would see intel, amd or motorola working on it. They can afford to @#%$ $billions away making each new cpu, a few hundred million $ would be easy to lose in the noise of their budgets.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td class="row2" width="150" align="left" valign="middle"><span class="nav"><a href="#top" class="nav">Back to top</a></span></td>
