	<tr>
		<td class="spaceRow" colspan="2" height="1"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/spacer.gif" alt="" width="1" height="1" /></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><span class="name"><a name="72113"></a><b>EvilNight</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">Agent of the System<br />
		<br /><img class="avatar" src="http://www.eqluclin.com/forum/images/avatars/bunbun.gif" alt="" /><br />
		<br />Joined: 19 Jul 2003<br />Posts: 1507</span></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=72113&amp;sid=82260115d6e1a7fd6d33fd52a8a3fef5#72113"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Thu Jun 24, 2004 7:07 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Re: Excerpt from &quot;The Isaiah Effect&quot;</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=72113&amp;sid=82260115d6e1a7fd6d33fd52a8a3fef5"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> What we are saying, that the ideas you proposed to be absolute truth in Kurzweils article are highly improbable in the timeframe that was proposed. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I stated repeately that the only problem I had with his article was the timeframe for many reasons, underdevelopment being chief among them. I still think his entire paper is very sound, however. I'd say 100 years is optimistic, 500 years is pessimistic. Somewhere in that range. Say 2401.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">However, due to your, poppas and Kurzweils poor conception of what evolution is about and how the inner workings in the thoughts of the Evolution Theory fit together</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I have a very good grasp of evolution. What I'm saying is that its definition is going to change by the very nature of the technology we are creating. Let me see if I can explain this to you in normal evolution terms so you see what I'm talking about.
<br />

<br />
A given species evolves over millions of years. The evolution comes in the form of tiny, miniscule mutations that give certain members of the species who have them an edge over those who do not. Those with this edge are better able to compete for food and mates, and their offspring are therefore likely to be more numberous and better equipped due to inheriting this edge. Is this not a simplistic description of basic evolution? All evolution theory follows from this one guiding principle.
<br />

<br />
Compare that with this.
<br />

<br />
A given species evolves over a hundred years. The evolution comes in the form of changes this species makes consciously to its own body. These changes, if found to be valuable, are then made to all remaining members of the species willing and able to receive them. Those who acquire these changes acquire an edge over those who choose not to take them or can not acclimate to them. Those with this edge live longer, acquire greater skill sets and more intelligence, and are better able to compete for valuable resources and for mates (or have more offspring over the course of a longer life).
<br />

<br />
I see no difference between these two scenarios. Both are guided by the environment. Both prefer mutations that are beneficial to the species within their environment. Only the rate of change is different; with conscious direction the rate of evolution increases dramatically.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> (note I said mind, not brain as youre all saying brains will no longer be needed in a few years!) </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The health of the mind is a very different matter. No one can say how longevity or a radical change in human physiology will affect the human mind until it's been done. I wouldn't be surprised in the least to encounter some very serious mental health issues (that have nothing to do with biology) related to advancing age (over 120+ years), or problems coping with having fifty times a human's normal cognitive capacity. What you are really testing there is the mind's capability to evolve and adapt to radical changes. That's the kind of thing that has to be done to be understood. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> <span style="font-style: italic">As for you seeing a high rate of evolution in todays ever-changing world due to human interaction? Id like to see some primary research that might suggest this is the case.</span> Everything is always facing selective pressures (yes, humans included; Although our pressures are mainly sexual selective in nature, as we are our own environment of evolutionary adaptiveness). Due to the radical changes we bring to todays environment, and due to the specie pollution we have introduced for the past four hundred years, <span style="font-style: italic">Id say more species are going extinct than are radically changing.</span> </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
To me this seems a contradiction. You admit that more species are going extinct (failing at evolution, essentially), yet you do not see how this indicates a changing environment (caused by us) that fosters rapid evolution?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> You cannot however design an optimal biological organism to ANY environment using evolution. Technology improves as time goes on, however it does not follow evolutionary trends. Improvement over time!= evolution in a biological sense, and relating technology and biology improvements in such a fashion ends there. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Again, I see no difference between a billion years of evolution in a given environment producing an organism, and fifty years of hard research and engineering producing a similar or better organism.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Furthermore, any argument Kurzweil has in his article about evolution is false. He argues that evolution is on an exponential increase in changes. It does not however follow such a trend. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I think you misinterpreted the point he was trying to make. He is merely saying that if our technology reaches the point where we can use it to better ourselves in an evolutionary sense (building a better human being), evolution will take on technology's exponential traits as the two merge and become inseperable. To me this seems a logical conclusion to draw.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Species themselves do not evolve faster today than they did yesterday.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
This is true, if you look at it from a perspective of generation by generation... the mutation rate is not significantly higher, therefore the rate of permanent evolutionary change did not increase. If the envoronment changes faster than the species can keep up, it becomes extinct. Evolution favors the adaptive species. Nothing is more adaptive than mankind.
<br />

<br />
Toss technology into the mix, however, and you don't need to have offspring. You can re-engineer the existing being, over time, into something that hardly resembles its original state. Any changes to their genetics you choose to make are also passed along to their offspring, so in effect you are changing the species the same way evolution does, just in a far more intelligent and far better fashion (and in a lot less time).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> You have seen a recent increase in the rate of which new technologies come about, however that is due to the amount of money that is gained by providing new technologies, combined with the amount of new engineers that are entering the new technologies field. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
New technology means better, faster, cheaper. Even with a finite, unchanging amount of resources, this means that given enough time, we can better our tools to the point of being adequate to accomplish any task. The amount of resources does change, however... it is constantly on the rise as we become more and more skilled at transforming raw materials into the resources we need.
<br />

<br />
Consider the amount of money and scientific power the world would have if the EU, Russia, China, India, Australia, and the Middle East reached western levels of development, science, and economic power. The world's resources are not finite, they are increasing. The efficiency of our use of those resources is also increasing. That resource will eventually come to a cap unless we bring in resources from off of the planet, however I think we have a very long way to go before we max out earth's resources.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> keep in mind, your personal computer may be powerful and smart, however take a look at the PCM in your car, or the Power distribution box or junction box in your car and realize that those technologies are, in some cases, decades old. Why? Because it is not cost effective to improve them beyond their current states. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The car has evolved pretty mcuh as far as it needs to, for now. Right now vehicular evolution is more concerned with fuel efficiency. Rest assured if that PCM chip represented a limitng factor that was preventing something important from being done, it would be upgraded in a heartbeat.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> MAIN POINT: Techonolgy only improves in todays world if there is money to be made. It is not an evolutionary process just because it improves. This is world is not a member of the Federation in Star Trek. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Yes, this is part of the beauty in capitalism. One of humanity's worst traits (greed, which happens to be one of humanity's BEST traits in an evolutionary sense) drives on this engine of technology and progress. Every improvement in technology means more money for the inventor, more money for the builder, and a better product for the buyer. One could almost argue that greed is going to take us to a place we are not morally ready to go long before we would have otherwise gotten there. This greed is going to drive our technology along at its current breakneck pace until humanity reaches some kind of a turning point.
<br />

<br />
Star Trek's vision of the future, while entertaining, is a far cry from realistic. It's modern-man in space, not future-man in space. 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> If genetic engineering becomes trivial, you should become very scared. I can consider several thingies that will result in a lot of grief: </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Regarding 1-8, you are quite correct. The technology brings with it the capability for massive destruction. The only way to counter such a threat, however, is with the same technology that created it. Kurzweil makes a few points about this as well... namely that the research will be done in secret if it is outlawed, so the best choice is to stay the course, make sure those with the greatest sense of responsibility and safety are the ones who complete it first, and to prepare for the worst. I think he is quite right about this as well. 
<br />

<br />
It's not a no-risk proposition. It's gravely dangerous. It's still going to happen, one way or another.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Optronics (or photonics) has been lab stuff for 20+ years. We've had it since the late 70s. I will believe when I see chips come out. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I linked you to a protoype. You do know what a prototype is, Mr. Engineer, don't you? A working, functioning model that you can touch that performs as they claim it does? A first step on the way to mass production? Do you need to have physical access to the room it is in so that you can touch it to believe it is real?<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
